1. PASSWORD COMPLEXITY / pwquality
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: Password 'difok' setting not configured
FIX:
  Edit /etc/security/pwquality.conf OR /etc/security/pwquality.conf.d/*.conf
  Set the 'difok' value according to business needs and org security policies.

  Example:
    echo "difok = 5" >> /etc/security/pwquality.conf


--------------------------------------------------------------------
2. UNOWNED FILES ON SYSTEM
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: Files found with no valid owner user ID or group ID
FIX:
  Run the following to find and fix unowned files:
    find / -nouser -o -nogroup 2>/dev/null
  Update ownership or remove files as per org security policies.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
3. PAM_PWQUALITY MODULE
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: pam_pwquality module not installed/configured
FIX:
  Install the module:
    apt install libpam-pwquality

  Then configure /etc/pam.d/common-password to enforce complexity.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
4. SSH DenyGroups SETTING
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: DenyGroups not configured in sshd_config
FIX:
  Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/*.conf
  Add or set:
    DenyGroups <groupname>
  Adjust to business needs and org security policies.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
5. SSH DenyUsers SETTING
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: DenyUsers not configured in sshd_config
FIX:
  Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/*.conf
  Add:
    DenyUsers <username>
  Adjust to business needs and org security policies.


--------------------------------------------------------------------
6. IPTABLES - CONFIGURE AND ENABLE
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: iptables rules not configured per security policy
FIX:
  Run the following command to enable and start iptables:
    systemctl enable iptables
    systemctl start iptables

  Configure rules per the business requirements or org security policy.
  Example default deny:
    iptables -P INPUT DROP
    iptables -P FORWARD DROP
    iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
    iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
    iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT


--------------------------------------------------------------------
7. PAM CONSECUTIVE FAILED LOGINS / pam_faillock
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: Brute force lockout policy not configured
FIX:
  Edit /etc/pam.d/common-auth
  Configure this setting according to business needs and org security policies.

  Example (add to common-auth):
    auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent audit deny=5 unlock_time=900
    auth [default=die] pam_faillock.so authfail audit deny=5 unlock_time=900


--------------------------------------------------------------------
8. STICKY BIT ON WORLD-WRITABLE DIRECTORIES
--------------------------------------------------------------------
ISSUE: World-writable directories do not have sticky bit set
FIX:
  Find and fix world-writable directories:
    find / -xdev -type d -perm -0002 ! -perm -1000 2>/dev/null | xargs chmod +t

  The sticky bit ensures only the file owner can delete files in the directory.


